Looks much better. Two more comments:
1. It would be good to print the exception in addition to failing the test, because otherwise the tests only fails and gives no indication why. A typical pattern is:

``` java
try {
  // some stuff
} catch (Exception e) {
  e.printStackTrace();
  Assert.fail(e.getMessage());
}
```

Here, the test prints nothing when working properly, but prints the error when it fails.
1. `Assert.fail()` does not work when used in spawned threads. The reason is that JUnit communicates the failure with a special `AssertionFailedException`, which needs to reach the invoking framework. That does not happen if the `fail()` method is called in a spawned thread.

Here is how you can do it. It is a bit clumsy, because you need to forward the exception to the main thread, but it works well:

``` java
final AtomicReference<Throwable> error = new AtomicReference<>();
Thread thread = new Thread("server thread") {
    @Override
    public void run() {
        try {
            doStuff();
        }
        catch (Throwable t) {
            ref.set(t);
        }
    }
};
thread.start();

// do some test logic

thread.join();
if (error.get() != null) {
    Throwable t = error.get();
    t.printStackTrace();
    fail("Error in spawned thread: " + t.getMessage());
}
```

